where Pjik and Pji(k−1) are the probabilities of scoring k and k− 1 on item i for person j, respectively; θj is the latent trait of person j and is assumed to be distributed normally with a mean of zero; δi is the location of item i; and τk (
k = 1 , … , C
) is the kth threshold parameter for all items. The τ parameters do not have subscript i, indicating that all items share the same set of τ parameters, which is justifiable for rating scale items, because they are scored according to a common scoring rubric (e.g., 0 = seldom, 1 = sometimes, 2 = often, and 3 = always). In addition, the τ parameters are fixed effects, meaning that they remain constant across persons. This assumption of fixed effects is justifiable when item responses can be marked objectively via clear scoring rubrics (e.g., objective items that can be scored by computers). In responding to rating scale items, persons are asked to select one from a set of given categories. The selection involves subjective judgment of the categories and the thresholds between them. For instance, a person may consider the gap between “seldom” and “sometimes” to be small and the gap between “sometimes” and “often” to be large, whereas another person may have the opposite view. In other words, different persons may apply the rating scale that is imposed on them differently. Under such circumstances, fixed-effect item parameters for all persons may be too stringent, because they do not consider variation in subjective judgment across persons.
